{{Infobox organization |name = Douglas–Coldwell Foundation |image = Douglas-Coldwell Foundation.png |image_border = |size = |alt = |caption = |map = |msize = |malt = |mcaption = |map2 = |abbreviation = DCF |motto = |predecessor = |successor = |formation = {{Start date|1971}} |extinction = |type = |status = [[Charitable organizations (Canada)|Charitable organization]] |purpose = |headquarters = [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]] |location = |coords = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> |region_served = [[Canada]] |membership = |language = |general = |leader_title = President |leader_name = [[Karl Bélanger]] |leader_title2 = |leader_name2 = |leader_title3 = |leader_name3 = |leader_title4 = |leader_name4 = |key_people = |main_organ = |parent_organization = |affiliations = |budget = |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |website = {{official URL}} |remarks = |former name = }} The '''Douglas–Coldwell Foundation''' is a left-wing [[Canada|Canadian]] [[think tank]] devoted, in the words of its slogan, to "promoting education and research into [[social democracy]]." It was founded in 1971, and is based in [[Ottawa]].
The Foundation was named for and inspired by [[Tommy Douglas]], the first federal leader of the [[New Democratic Party (Canada)|New Democratic Party]] from 1961 to 1971, and [[Major James Coldwell|M. J. Coldwell]], leader of its predecessor [[Co-operative Commonwealth Federation]] from 1942 to 1960. Both had desired a Canadian counterpart to the [[Fabian Society]].
In 1987, it merged with the Ontario Woodsworth Memorial Foundation of [[Toronto]], named for Coldwell's predecessor as CCF leader, [[J. S. Woodsworth]].
The foundation has underwritten biographies of Douglas, Coldwell, [[Clarence Gillis]], [[Stanley Knowles]], and [[Grace MacInnis]], and scholarships and lectureships at Canadian post-secondary institutions. The foundation also gives out yearly grants totalling up to $25,000 for projects supporting its mandate of "promoting education and research in social democracy."
The foundation is a registered [[Charitable organization|charitable]] foundation, contributions to which are [[tax deduction|tax-deductible]] in Canada; it accepts memberships and solicits donations from individuals and organizations in the general public. While predominantly associated with NDP members and activists, and concerned in part with the history and future of the party, it is an independent group with no administrative connection to any political party.
Tommy Douglas was the foundation's first president. [[Kalmen Kaplansky]] led the think tank in the 1980s and 1990s. [[Karl Bélanger]] became president of the foundation in November 2016.<ref>[http://en.dcf.ca/2016nov24president The Douglas-Coldwell Foundation elects Karl Bélanger as President] ''Douglas-Coldwell Foundation'', November 24, 2016.</ref>
